{{Women in society sidebar}}
'''Women in computing''' have shaped the evolution of [[information technology]]. They were among the first programmers in the early-20th century, and contributed substantially to the industry. As technology and practices altered, the role of women as programmers has changed, and the recorded history of the field has downplayed their achievements.

Since the 18th century, women have developed scientific computations, including [[Nicole-Reine Lepaute]]'s prediction of [[Halley's Comet]], and [[Maria Mitchell]]'s computation of the motion of [[Venus]]. The first [[algorithm]] intended to be executed by a computer was designed by [[Ada Lovelace]] who was a pioneer in the field. [[Grace Hopper]] was the first person to design a [[compiler]] for a [[programming language]]. Throughout the 19th and early-20th century, and up to [[World War II]], programming was predominantly done by women; significant examples include the [[Harvard Computers]], codebreaking at [[Bletchley Park]] and engineering at [[NASA]].

After the 1960s, the "soft work" that had been dominated by women evolved into modern [[software]], and the importance of women decreased. The gender disparity and the lack of women in computing from the late 20th century onward has been examined, but no firm explanations have been established. Nevertheless, many women continued to make significant and important contributions to the IT industry, and attempts were made to readdress the gender disparity in the industry. In the 21st century, women held leadership roles in multiple tech companies, such as [[Meg Whitman]], president and chief executive officer of [[Hewlett Packard Enterprise]], and [[Marissa Mayer]], president and CEO of [[Yahoo!]] and key spokesperson at [[Google]].

==History==
{{See also|Timeline of women in computing}}

=== 1700s ===
[[Nicole-Reine Lepaute|Nicole-Reine Etable de la Brière Lepaute]] was one of a team of [[Human computer|human computers]] who worked with [[Alexis Clairaut|Alexis-Claude Clairaut]] and [[Jérôme Lalande|Joseph-Jérôme Le Français de Lalande]] to predict the date of the return of [[Halley's Comet]].{{Sfn|Grier|2013|p=16}} They began work on the calculations in 1757, working throughout the day and sometimes during mealtimes.{{Sfn|Grier|2013|p=20-21}} Their methods were followed by successive human computers.{{Sfn|Grier|2013|p=25}} They divided large calculations into "independent pieces, assembled the results from each piece into a final product" and then checked for errors.{{Sfn|Grier|2013|p=25}} Lepaute continued to work on computing for the rest of her life, working for the [[Connaissance des Temps|''Connaissance de Temps'']] and publishing predictions of [[Solar eclipse|solar eclipses]].{{Sfn|Grier|2013|p=24}}

=== 1800s ===
[[File:Astronomer_Edward_Charles_Pickering's_Harvard_computers.jpg|thumb|left|Astronomer Edward Charles Pickering's [[Harvard Computers|Harvard computers]]]]
One of the first computers for the American ''[[Nautical almanac|Nautical Almanac]]'' was [[Maria Mitchell|Maria Mitchel]].{{Sfn|Grier|2013|p=61}} Her work on the assignment was to compute the motion of the planet [[Venus]].{{Sfn|Grier|2013|p=62}} The ''Almanac'' never became a reality, but Mitchell became the first [[astronomy]] professor at [[Vassar College|Vassar]].{{Sfn|Grier|2013|p=71}}

[[Ada Lovelace]] was the first person to publish an [[algorithm]] intended to be executed by the first modern computer, the [[Analytical Engine]] created by [[Charles Babbage]]. As a result she is often regarded as the first computer [[programmer]].<ref name="Annals of the History of Computing">{{cite journal|first=J.|last=Fuegi|first2=J.|last2=Francis|title=Lovelace & Babbage and the creation of the 1843 'notes'|journal=Annals of the History of Computing|volume=25|issue=4 |date=2003|pages=16–26|doi=10.1109/MAHC.2003.1253887}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last=Phillips|first=Ana Lena|title=Crowdsourcing gender equity: Ada Lovelace Day, and its companion website, aims to raise the profile of women in science and technology|journal=American Scientist|date=November–December 2011|volume=99|issue=6|page=463}}</ref><ref name="Lovelace Google">{{Cite news|date=December 10, 2012|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2012/dec/10/ada-lovelace-honoured-google-doodle|title=Ada Lovelace honoured by Google doodle|newspaper=The Guardian|accessdate=December 10, 2012}}</ref> Lovelace was introduced to Babbage's [[difference engine]] when she was 17.{{Sfn|Evans|2018|p=16}} In 1840, she wrote to Babbage and asked if she could become involved with his first machine.{{Sfn|Evans|2018|p=17}} By this time, Babbage had moved on to his idea for the Analytical Engine.{{Sfn|Evans|2018|p=18}} A paper describing the Analytical Engine, ''Notions sur la machine analytique'', published by L.F. Menabrea, came to the attention of Lovelace, who not only translated it into English, but corrected mistakes made by Menabrea.{{Sfn|Evans|2018|p=19}} Babbage suggested that she expand the translation of the paper with her own ideas, which, signed only with her initials, AAL, "synthesized the vast scope of Babbage's vision."{{Sfn|Evans|2018|p=19-20}} Lovelace imagined the kind of impact of the Analytical Engine might have on society.{{Sfn|Evans|2018|p=20}} She drew up explanations of how the engine could handle inputs, outputs, processing and data storage.{{Sfn|Evans|2018|p=21}} She also created several [[Mathematical proof|proofs]] to show how the engine would handle calculations of [[Bernoulli number|Bernoulli Numbers]] on its own.{{Sfn|Evans|2018|p=21}} The proofs are considered the first examples of a computer program.{{Sfn|Evans|2018|p=21}}<ref name="Annals of the History of Computing" /> Lovelace downplayed her role in her work during her life, for example, in signing her contributions with AAL so as not be "accused of bragging."{{Sfn|Smith|2013|p=5}}

After the [[American Civil War|Civil War]] in the United States, more women were hired as human computers.{{Sfn|Grier|2013|p=81}} Many were war widows looking for ways to support themselves.{{Sfn|Grier|2013|p=81}} Others were hired when the government opened positions to women because of a shortage of men to fill the roles.{{Sfn|Grier|2013|p=81}}

[[File:Annie Jump Cannon sitting at desk.jpg|thumb|[[Annie Jump Cannon]] working at Harvard]]
[[Anna Winlock]] asked to become a computer for the Harvard Observatory in 1875 and was hired to work for 25 cents an hour.{{Sfn|Grier|2013|p=82}} By 1880, [[Edward Charles Pickering]] had hired several women to work for him at [[Harvard University|Harvard]] because he felt that women could do the job as well as men and he could ask them to volunteer or work for less pay.{{Sfn|Sobel|2016|p=13}}{{Sfn|Grier|2013|p=82}} The women, described as "Pickering's harem" and also as the [[Harvard Computers]], performed clerical work that the male employees and scholars considered to be tedious at a fraction of the cost of hiring a man.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.atlasobscura.com/articles/how-female-computers-mapped-the-universe-and-brought-america-to-the-moon|title=How Female Computers Mapped the Universe and Brought America to the Moon|date=March 4, 2016|work=Atlas Obscura|access-date=September 29, 2017|language=en}}</ref> The women working for Pickering cataloged around ten thousand stars, discovered the [[Horsehead Nebula]] and developed the system to describe stars.{{Sfn|Evans|2018|p=23}} One of the "computers," [[Annie Jump Cannon]], could classify stars at a rate of three stars per minute.{{Sfn|Evans|2018|p=23}} The work for Pickering became so popular that women volunteered to work for free even when the computers were being paid.{{Sfn|Sobel|2016|p=105}} Even though they performed an important role, the Harvard Computers were paid less than [[factory]] workers.{{Sfn|Evans|2018|p=23}}

By the 1890s, women computers were college graduates looking for jobs where they could use their training in a useful way.{{Sfn|Grier|2013|p=103}} Florence Tebb Weldon, was part of this group and provided computations relating to biology and evidence for [[evolution]], working with her husband, W.F. Raphael Weldon.{{Sfn|Grier|2013|p=106}} Florence Weldon's calculations demonstrated that statistics could be used to support [[Charles Darwin|Darwin's]] theory of evolution.{{Sfn|Grier|2013|p=107}} Another human computer involved in biology was [[Alice Lee (mathematician)|Alice Lee]], who worked with [[Karl Pearson]].{{Sfn|Grier|2013|p=110}} Pearson hired two sisters to work as part-time computers at his Biometrics Lab, [[Beatrice Mabel Cave-Browne-Cave|Beatrice]] and [[Frances Cave-Browne-Cave|Frances Cave-Brown-Cave]].{{Sfn|Grier|2013|p=112}}

=== 1910s ===
During [[World War I]], Karl Pearson and his Biometrics Lab helped produce [[ballistics]] calculations for the British [[Minister of Munitions|Ministry of Munitions]].{{Sfn|Grier|2013|p=130}} Beatrice Cave-Brown-Cave helped calculate trajectories for bomb shells.{{Sfn|Grier|2013|p=130}} In 1916, Cave-Brown-Cave left Pearson's employ and started working full-time for the Ministry.{{Sfn|Grier|2013|p=131}} In the United States, women computers were hired to calculate ballistics in 1918, working in a building on the [[Washington Mall]].{{Sfn|Grier|2013|p=138}} One of the women, Elizabeth Webb Wilson, worked as the chief computer.{{Sfn|Grier|2013|p=139}} After the war, women who worked as ballistics computers for the U.S. government had trouble finding jobs in computing and Wilson eventually taught high school math.{{Sfn|Grier|2013|p=152}}

=== 1920s ===
[[File:Bell telephone magazine (1922) (14570000517).jpg|thumb|upright|A group of operators working on an [[AT&T Corporation|AT&T]] telephone switchboard]]
In the early 1920s, [[Iowa State University|Iowa State College]], professor [[George W. Snedecor|George Snedecor]] worked to improve the school's science and engineering departments, experimenting with new punch-card machines and calculators.{{Sfn|Grier|2013|p=165-166}} Snedecor also worked with human calculators most of them women, including Mary Clem.{{Sfn|Grier|2013|p=167}} Clem coined the term "zero check" to help identify errors in calculations.{{Sfn|Grier|2013|p=167}} The computing lab, run by Clem, became one of the most powerful computing facilities of the time.{{Sfn|Grier|2013|p=167}}{{Sfn|Grier|2013|p=169}} 

Women computers also worked at the [[AT&T Corporation|American Telephone and Telegraph]] company.{{Sfn|Grier|2013|p=170}} These human computers worked with [[Electrical engineering|electrical engineers]] to help figure out how to boost signals with [[vacuum tube]] amplifiers.{{Sfn|Grier|2013|p=170}} One of the computers, Clara Froelich, was eventually moved along with the other computers to their own division where they worked with a mathematician, Thornton Fry, to create new computational methods.{{Sfn|Grier|2013|p=170}} Froelich studied IBM [[Tabulating machine|tabulating equipment]] and desk calculating machines to see if she could adapt the machine method to calculations.{{Sfn|Grier|2013|p=170-171}}

[[Edith Clarke]] was the first woman to earn a degree in [[electrical engineering]] and who worked as the first professionally employed electrical engineer in the United States.<ref name=":10">{{Cite news|url=https://www.ge.com/reports/edith-clarke-mother-of-invention/|title=Mother Of Invention: This Barrier-Busting Electrical Engineer Joined Edison, Tesla in National Inventors Hall of Fame – GE Reports|last=Kellner|first=Tomas|date=2017-02-10|work=GE Reports|access-date=2018-11-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180825185215/https://www.ge.com/reports/edith-clarke-mother-of-invention/|archive-date=25 August 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> She was hired by [[General Electric]] as a full engineer in 1923.<ref name=":10" /> Clarke also filed a patent in 1921 for a [[graphical calculator]] to be used in solving problems in power lines.<ref name=":72">{{Cite web|url=https://www.women.cs.cmu.edu/ada/Resources/Women/|title=Pioneering Women in Computer Technology|last=|first=|date=|website=The Ada Project|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180326031002/https://www.women.cs.cmu.edu/ada/Resources/Women/|archive-date=26 March 2018|dead-url=|access-date=22 November 2018}}</ref> It was granted in 1925.<ref name=":10" />

=== 1930s ===
The [[National Advisory Committee for Aeronautics]] (NACA) which became [[NASA]] hired a group of five women in 1935 to work as a computer pool.<ref name=":1">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nasa.gov/larc/from-computers-to-leaders-women-at-nasa-langley|title=From Computers to Leaders: Women at NASA Langley|last=Atkinson|first=Joe|date=August 24, 2015|work=NASA|access-date=October 14, 2018|language=en}}</ref> The women worked on the data coming from [[wind tunnel]] and flight tests.<ref name=":1" />

=== 1940s ===
[[File:'bombe'.jpg|alt=Woman working on a Bombe computing device.|thumb|left|Woman working on a [[Bombe]] computing device.]]
"Tedious" computing and calculating was seen as "women's work" through the 1940s{{Sfn|Mundy|2017|p=21}} resulting in the term "kilogirl", invented by a member of the [[Applied Mathematics Panel]] in the early 1940s.{{Sfn|Evans|2018|p=24}} A kilogirl of energy was "equivalent to roughly a thousand hours of computing labor."{{Sfn|Evans|2018|p=24}} While women's contributions to the United States war effort during [[World War II]] was championed in the media, their roles and the work they did was minimized.{{Sfn|Light|1999|p=455-456}} This included minimizing the complexity, skill and knowledge needed to work on computers or work as human computers.{{Sfn|Light|1999|p=455-456}} During WWII, women did most of the ballistics computing, seen by male engineers as being below their level of expertise.{{Sfn|Light|1999|p=460}}  [[Black women]] computers worked as hard (or more often, twice as hard) as their white counterparts, but in segregated situations.{{Sfn|Shetterly|2016|p=47-48}} By 1943, almost all people employed as computers were women.{{Sfn|Smith|2013|p=6}}

NACA expanded its a pool of women human computers in the 1940s.{{Sfn|Shetterly|2016|p=39}} NACA recognized in 1942 that "the engineers admit themselves that the girl computers do the work more rapidly and accurately than they could."<ref name=":1" /> In 1943 two groups, segregated by race, worked on the east and west side of [[Langley Air Force Base]].{{Sfn|Shetterly|2016|p=39}} The black women were the [[West Area Computers]].{{Sfn|Shetterly|2016|p=39}} Unlike their white counterparts, the black women were asked by NACA to re-do college courses they had already passed and many never received promotions.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.popularmechanics.com/space/rockets/a24429/hidden-figures-real-story-nasa-women-computers/|title=The True Story of 'Hidden Figures' and the Women Who Crunched the Numbers for NASA|last=Blitz|first=Matt|date=February 3, 2017|work=Popular Mechanics|access-date=October 18, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>

Women were also working on ballistic missile calculations. In 1948, women such as [[Barbara Paulson]] were working on the [[WAC Corporal]], determining trajectories the missiles would take after launch.{{Sfn|Holt|2016|p=58-59}}

Women worked with [[cryptography]] and, after some initial resistance, many operated and worked on the [[Bombe]] machines.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/women-were-key-code-breaking-bletchley-park-180954044/|title=Women Were Key to WWII Code-Breaking at Bletchley Park|last=Fessenden|first=Marissa|work=Smithsonian|access-date=October 14, 2018|language=en}}</ref> [[Joyce Aylard]] operated the Bombe machine testing different methods to break the [[Enigma machine|Enigma code]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.theguardian.com/careers/2018/jul/24/meet-the-female-codebreakers-of-bletchley-park|title=Meet the female codebreakers of Bletchley Park|last=Bearne|first=Suzanne|date=July 24, 2018|newspaper=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=October 14, 2018}}</ref> [[Joan Clarke]] was a cryptographer who worked with her friend, [[Alan Turing]], on the Enigma machine at [[Bletchley Park]].<ref name=":0">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-29840653|title=The woman who cracked Enigma cyphers|last=Miller|first=Joe|date=November 10, 2014|work=BBC News|access-date=October 14, 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref> When she was promoted to a higher salary grade, there were no positions in the civil service for a "senior female cryptanalyst," and she was listed as a linguist instead.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://theinstitute.ieee.org/ieee-roundup/members/achievements/women-code-breakers-forgotten-by-history|title=Women Code Breakers: Forgotten by History|last=Pretz|first=Kathy|date=February 5, 2015|website=The Institute|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=October 14, 2018}}</ref> While Clarke developed a method of increasing the speed of double-encrypted messages, unlike many of the men, her decryption technique was not named after her.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cosmosmagazine.com/technology/joan-clarke-one-of-the-forgotten-women-of-bletchley|title=Joan Clarke, one of the forgotten women of Bletchley|last=Condie|first=Bill|date=May 14, 2015|website=Cosmos|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=October 14, 2018}}</ref> Other cryptographers at Bletchley included [[Margaret Rock]], [[Mavis Batey|Mavis Lever]] (later Batey), Ruth Briggs and Kerry Howard.<ref name=":0" /> In 1941, Batey's work enabled the [[Allies of World War II|Allies]] to break the Italian's naval code before the [[Battle of Cape Matapan]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.pri.org/stories/2014-12-23/alan-turing-may-have-cracked-nazi-codes-thousands-women-helped|title=Alan Turing may have cracked Nazi codes, but thousands of women helped|last=Porzucki|first=Nina|date=December 23, 2014|work=Public Radio International|access-date=October 14, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> In the United States, several faster Bombe machines were created.{{Sfn|Mundy|2017|p=270-271}} Women, like Louise Pearsall, were recruited from the [[WAVES]] to work on code breaking and operate the American Bombe machines.{{Sfn|Mundy|2017|p=271-272}}

[[Hedy Lamarr]] and co-inventor, [[George Antheil|George Anthei]]<nowiki/>l, worked on a [[Frequency-hopping spread spectrum|frequency hopping]] method to help the Navy control torpedoes remotely.<ref name=":5" /> The Navy passed on their idea, but Lamarr and Antheil received a patent for the work on August 11, 1942.<ref name=":5" /> This technique would later be used again, first in the 1950s at Sylvania Electronic Systems Division and is used in everyday technology such as [[Bluetooth]] and [[Wi-Fi]].<ref name=":5" />
[[File:Reprogramming_ENIAC.png|alt=Marlyn Wescoff, standing, and Ruth Lichterman reprogram the ENIAC in 1946.|thumb|[[Marlyn Meltzer|Marlyn Wescoff,]] standing, and [[Ruth Teitelbaum|Ruth Lichterman]] reprogram the [[ENIAC]] in 1946.]]
The programmers of the [[ENIAC]] computer in 1944, were six female mathematicians; [[Marlyn Meltzer]], [[Betty Holberton]], [[Kathleen Antonelli]], [[Ruth Teitelbaum]], [[Jean Bartik]], and [[Frances Spence]] who were human computers at the [[Moore School of Electrical Engineering|Moore School's]] computation lab.{{Sfn|Evans|2018|p=39}} [[Adele Goldstine]] was their teacher and trainer and they were known as the "ENIAC girls."{{Sfn|Light|1999|p=459}} The women who worked on ENIAC were warned that they would not be promoted into professional ratings which were only for men.{{Sfn|Gürer|1995|p=177}} Designing the hardware was "men's work" and programming the software was "women's work."{{Sfn|Light|1999|p=469}}  Sometimes women were given [[blueprint]]s and [[wiring diagram]]s to figure out how the machine worked and how to program it.{{Sfn|Light|1999|p=470}} They learned how the ENIAC worked by repairing it, sometimes crawling through the computer, and by fixing "bugs" in the machinery.{{Sfn|Light|1999|p=470}} Even though the programmers were supposed to be doing the "soft" work of programming, in reality, they did that and fully understood and worked with the hardware of the ENIAC.{{Sfn|Light|1999|p=471}} When the ENIAC was revealed in 1946, Goldstine and the other women prepared the machine and the demonstration programs it ran for the public.{{Sfn|Light|1999|p=472}} None of their work in preparing the demonstrations was mentioned in the official accounts of the public events.{{Sfn|Light|1999|p=473}} After the demonstration, the university hosted an expensive celebratory dinner to which none of the ENIAC six were invited.{{Sfn|Evans|2018|p=51}}

In Canada, [[Beatrice Worsley]] started working at the [[National Research Council (Canada)|National Research Council of Canada]] in 1947 where she was an aerodynamics research officer.<ref name=":12">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/beatrice-worsley|title=Beatrice Worsley|last=Raymond|first=Katrine|date=25 October 2017|website=The Canadian Encyclopedia|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180113171457/http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/beatrice-worsley/|archive-date=13 January 2018|dead-url=|access-date=2018-11-23}}</ref> A year later, she started working in the new Computational Centre at the [[University of Toronto]].<ref name=":12" /> She built a [[Differential analyser|differential analyzer]] in 1948 and also worked with IBM machines in order to do calculations for [[Atomic Energy of Canada Limited]].<ref name=":12" /> She went to study the [[EDSAC]] at the [[University of Cambridge]] in 1949.<ref name=":12" /> She wrote the program that was run the first time EDSAC performed its first calculations on May 6, 1949.<ref name=":12" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.computinghistory.org.uk/det/5484/EDSAC-performed-its-first-calculations/|title=EDSAC performed its first calculations|last=|first=|date=|website=Computing History|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-11-23}}</ref> 

[[Grace Hopper]] was the first person to create a [[compiler]] for a [[programming language]] and one of the first programmers of the [[Harvard Mark I]] computer, an electro-mechanical computer based on Analytical Engine. Hopper's work with computers started in 1943, when she started working at the [[Bureau of Ordnance]]'s Computation Project at Harvard where she programmed the Harvard Mark I.{{Sfn|Smith|2013|p=6}} Hopper not only programmed the computer, but created a 500 page comprehensive manual for it.{{Sfn|Smith|2013|p=7}} Even though Hopper created the manual which was widely cited and published, she was not specifically credited in the manual.{{Sfn|Smith|2013|p=7}} Hopper is often credited with the coining of the term "bug" and "[[debugging]]" when a moth caused the Mark II to malfunction.{{Sfn|Gürer|1995|p=176}} While a moth was found and the process of removing it called "debugging," the terms were already part of the language of programmers.{{Sfn|Gürer|1995|p=176}}<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.computerworld.com/article/2515435/app-development/moth-in-the-machine--debugging-the-origins-of--bug-.html|title=Moth in the machine: Debugging the origins of 'bug'|last=|first=|date=September 3, 2011|work=Computerworld|access-date=October 13, 2018|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wired.com/2013/12/googles-doodle-honors-grace-hopper-and-entomology/|title=Google Honors Grace Hopper...and a "bug"|last=Pearson|first=Gwen|date=December 9, 2013|work=WIRED|access-date=October 13, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>

=== 1950s ===
[[File:Annie_Easley_in_NASA.jpg|thumb|[[Annie Easley]] in NASA in 1955.]]
Grace Hopper continued to contribute to computer science through the 1950s. She brought the idea of using compilers from her time at Harvard to [[UNIVAC]] which she joined in 1949.{{Sfn|Ceruzzi|1998|p=84-85}}{{Sfn|Gürer|1995|p=176}} Other women who were hired to program UNIVAC included [[Adele Mildred Koss]], Frances E. Holberton, Jean Bartik, Frances Morello and Lillian Jay.{{Sfn|Gürer|1995|p=177}} To program the UNIVAC, Hopper and her team used the [[FLOW-MATIC]] programming language, which she developed.{{Sfn|Gürer|1995|p=176}} Holberton wrote a code, C-10, that allowed for [[Computer keyboard|keyboard]] inputs into a general-purpose computer.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/24508073|title=Frances Holberton, Pioneer in Computer Languages, Dies|last=|first=|date=December 12, 2001|work=The Courier-Journal|access-date=October 13, 2018|language=en|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Holberton also developed the [[Sort Merge Generator|Sort-Merge Generator]] in 1951 which was used on the [[UNIVAC I]].{{Sfn|Gürer|1995|p=177}} The Sort-Merge Generator marked the first time a computer "used a program to write a program."{{Sfn|Evans|2018|p=59}} Holberton suggested that computer housing should be beige or oatmeal in color which became a long-lasting trend.{{Sfn|Evans|2018|p=59}} Koss worked with Hopper on various algorithms and a program that was a precursor to a [[report generator]].{{Sfn|Gürer|1995|p=177}}

[[Klara Dan von Neumann]] was one of the main programmers of the [[MANIAC I|MANIAC]], a more advanced version of ENIAC.<ref name=":13">{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/marshallshepherd/2017/01/24/how-a-woman-you-never-heard-of-helped-enable-modern-weather-prediction/#364bc8f5195c|title=How A Woman You Never Heard Of Helped Enable Modern Weather Prediction|last=Shepherd|first=Marshall|date=24 January 2017|work=Forbes|access-date=2018-11-24|language=en}}</ref> Her work helped the field of meteorology and weather prediction.<ref name=":13" />

The NACA, and subsequently NASA, recruited women computers following World War II.<ref name=":1" /> By the 1950s, a team was performing mathematical calculations at the [[Lewis Research Center]] in [[Cleveland, Ohio]], including [[Annie Easley]], [[Katherine Johnson]] and [[Kathryn Peddrew]].{{sfn|Edwards|Harris|2016|pp=6,10}} At the [[National Institute of Standards and Technology|National Bureau of Standards]], [[Margaret R. Fox]] was hired to work as part of the technical staff of the Electronic Computer Laboratory in 1951.<ref name=":72" /> 

At [[Convair]] Aircraft Corporation, [[Joyce Currie Little]] was one of the original programmers for analyzing data received from the wind tunnels.{{Sfn|Gürer|1995|p=182}} She used [[Punched card|punch cards]] on an [[IBM 650]] which was located in a different building from the wind tunnel.{{Sfn|Gürer|1995|p=182}} To save time in the physical delivery of the punch cards, she and her colleague, Maggie DeCaro, put on [[roller skates]] to get to and from the building faster.{{Sfn|Gürer|1995|p=182}} 

In Israel, [[Thelma Estrin]] worked on the design and development of [[WEIZAC]], one of the world's first large-scale programmable electronic computers.{{Sfn|Gürer|1995|p=178}} In the [[Soviet Union]] the IT industry was dominated by women; a team of them designed the first digital computer in 1951.{{sfn|Abbate|2012|p=4}} In the UK[[Kathleen Booth|, Kathleen Booth]] worked with her husband, [[Andrew Donald Booth|Andrew Booth]] on several computers at [[Birkbeck, University of London|Birkbeck College]].<ref name=":11">{{Cite book|url=http://www.dcs.bbk.ac.uk/site/assets/files/1029/50yearsofcomputing.pdf|title=School of Computer Science & Information Systems: A Short History|last=Johnson|first=Roger|publisher=Birkbeck College, University of London|year=2008|isbn=|location=|pages=7-8}}</ref> Kathleen Booth was the programmer and Andrew built the machines.<ref name=":11" /> Kathleen developed [[Assembly language|Assembly Language]] at this time.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rte.ie/eile/brainstorm/2018/0110/932241-the-women-who-led-the-way-in-computer-programming/|title=The women who led the way in computer programming|last=Connolly|first=Cornelia|date=2018-01-10|work=RTE.ie|access-date=2018-11-25|last2=Hall|first2=Tony|language=en|last3=Lenaghan|first3=Jim}}</ref>

=== 1960s ===
[[File:Camp_Smith,_Hawaii._PFC_Patricia_Barbeau_operates_a_tape-drive_on_the_IBM_729_at_Camp_Smith._-_NARA_-_532417.tif|alt=PFC Patricia Barbeau operates a tape-drive on the IBM 729 at Camp Smith.|thumb|left|PFC Patricia Barbeau operates a tape-drive on the IBM 729 at Camp Smith.]]
Adele Mildred Koss, who had worked at UNIVAC with Hopper, started work at [[Control Data Corporation]] (CDC) in 1965.{{Sfn|Gürer|1995|p=177}} There she developed algorithms for graphics, including graphic storage and retrieval.{{Sfn|Gürer|1995|p=177}}

[[Mary K. Hawes]] of [[Burroughs Corporation|Burroghs Corporation]] set up a meeting in 1959 to discuss the creation a computer language that would be shared between businesses.{{Sfn|Gürer|1995|p=179}} Six people, including Hopper, attended to discuss the philosophy of creating a common business language (CBL).{{Sfn|Gürer|1995|p=179}} Hopper became involved in developing [[COBOL]] (Common Business Oriented Language) where she innovated new symbolic ways to write computer code.{{Sfn|Smith|2013|p=7}} Hopper developed programming language that was easier to read and "self-documenting."{{Sfn|Ceruzzi|1998|p=92}} After COBOL was submitted to the [[CODASYL]] Executive Committee, Betty Holberton did further editing on the language before it was submitted to the [[United States Government Publishing Office|Government Printing Office]] in 1960.{{Sfn|Gürer|1995|p=179}} IBM were slow to adopt COBOL, which hindered its progress but it was accepted as a standard in 1962, after Hopper had demonstrated the compiler working both on UNIVAC and RCA computers.{{sfn|Marx|2004|p=60}} The development of COBOL led to the generation of compilers and generators, most of which were created or refined by women such as Koss, Nora Moser, Deborah Davidson, Sue Knapp, Gertrude Tierney and [[Jean E. Sammet]].{{Sfn|Evans|2018|p=73}}

Sammet, who worked at IBM starting in 1961 was responsible for developing the programming language, [[FORMAC]].{{Sfn|Gürer|1995|p=179}} She  published a book, ''Programming Languages: History and Fundamentals'' (1969), which was considered the "standard work on programming languages," according to Denise Gürer {{Sfn|Gürer|1995|p=179}} It was "one of the most used books in the field," according to ''[[The Times (Shreveport)|The Times]]'' in 1972.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/24510360/|title=Computer Authority to Speak Here|last=|first=|date=April 9, 1972|work=The Times|access-date=October 13, 2018|language=en|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> 

Between 1961 and 1963, [[Margaret Hamilton (scientist)|Margaret Hamilton]] began to study software reliability while she was working at the US SAGE air defense system.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.computerhistory.org/fellowawards/hall/margaret-hamilton/|title=Margaret Hamilton|last=|first=|date=|website=Computer History Museum|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-11-18}}</ref> In 1965, she was responsible for programming the software for the onboard flight software on the [[Apollo program|Apollo mission]] computers.<ref name=":14">{{Cite news|url=https://www.wired.com/2015/10/margaret-hamilton-nasa-apollo/|title=Her Code Got Humans on the Moon—And Invented Software Itself|last=Harvey IV|first=Harry Gould|date=13 October 2015|work=WIRED|access-date=2018-11-24|language=en-US}}</ref> After Hamilton had completed the program, the code was sent to [[Raytheon]] where "expert seamstresses" called the "Little Old Ladies" actually hardwired the code by threading copper wire through magnetic rings.<ref name=":14" /> Each system could store more than 12,000 words that were represented by the copper wires.<ref name=":14" />

[[File:Katherine Johnson at NASA, in 1966.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Katherine Johnson]] working at [[NASA]] in 1966]]
In 1964, the British [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]] [[Harold Wilson]] announced a "White-Hot" revolution in technology, that would give greater prominence to IT work. As women still held most computing and programming positions at this time, it was hoped that it would give them more positive career prospects.{{sfn|Hicks|2017|p=14}} In 1965, [[Mary Kenneth Keller|Sister Mary Kenneth Keller]] became the first American woman to earn a doctorate in computer science.{{Sfn|Gürer|1995|p=180}} Keller helped develop [[BASIC]] while working as a graduate student at [[Dartmouth College|Dartmouth]], where the university "broke the 'men only' rule" so she could use its computer science center.{{Sfn|Gürer|1995|p=180-181}}

[[Christine Darden]] began working for NASA's computing pool in 1967 having graduated from the [[Hampton Institute]].{{sfn|Edwards|Harris|2016|p=50}} Women were involved in the development of [[Whirlwind I|Whirlwind]], including [[Judy Clapp]].{{Sfn|Gürer|1995|p=177}} She created the prototype for an air defense system for Whirlwind which used radar input to track planes in the air and could direct aircraft courses.{{Sfn|Gürer|1995|p=177}}

In 1969, [[Elizabeth J. Feinler|Elizabeth "Jake" Feinler]], who was working for [[Stanford University|Stanford]], made the first Resource Handbook for [[ARPANET]].{{Sfn|Evans|2018|p=112}} This led to the creation of the ARPANET directory, which was built by Feinler with a staff of mostly women.{{Sfn|Evans|2018|p=113}} Without the directory, "it was nearly impossible to navigate the ARPANET."{{Sfn|Evans|2018|p=116}} 

By the end of the decade, the general demographics of programmers had shifted away from being predominantly women, as they had before the 1940s.{{sfn|Hicks|2017|p=1}} Though women accounted for around 30 to 50 percent of computer programmers during the 1960s, few were promoted to leadership roles and women were paid significantly less than their male counterparts.{{Sfn|Evans|2018|p=76-77}} ''[[Cosmopolitan (magazine)|Cosmopolitan]]'' ran an article in the April 1967 issue about women in programming called "The Computer Girls."{{Sfn|Evans|2018|p=75}} Even while magazines such as ''Cosmopolitan'' saw a bright future for women in computers and computer programming in the 1960s, the reality was that women were still being marginalized.{{Sfn|Evans|2018|p=76}}

=== 1970s ===
[[File:No_original_caption._(African-American_woman_computer_operator)_-_NARA_-_558656.tif|alt=Using an NCR 796-201 cathode-ray terminal, circa 1972.|thumb|left|Using an NCR 796-201 cathode-ray terminal, circa 1972.]]
In the early 1970s, Pam Hardt-English led a group to create a computer network they named Resource One and which was part of a group called [[Project One (San Francisco)|Project One]].{{Sfn|Evans|2018|p=100}} Her idea to connect Bay Area bookstores, libraries and Project One was an early prototype of the [[Internet]].{{Sfn|Evans|2018|p=76}} To work on the project, Hardt-English obtained an expensive [[SDS 940|SDS-940]] computer as a donation from TransAmerica Leasing Corporation in April 1972.{{Sfn|Evans|2018|p=98}} They created an electronic library and housed it in a record store called Leopold's in Berkeley.{{Sfn|Evans|2018|p=101}} This became the Community Memory database and was maintained by hacker, [[Jude Milhon]].{{Sfn|Evans|2018|p=102}} After 1975, the SDS-940 computer was repurposed by Sherry Reson, Mya Shone, Chris Macie and Mary Janowitz to create a social services database and a Social Services Referral Directory.{{Sfn|Evans|2018|p=104-105}} Hard copies of the directory, printed out as a subscription service, were kept at city buildings and libraries.{{Sfn|Evans|2018|p=106-107}} The database was maintained and in use until 2009.{{Sfn|Evans|2018|p=107}}

In the early 1970s, Elizabeth "Jake" Feinler, who worked on the Resource Directory for ARPANET, and her team created the first [[WHOIS]] directory.{{Sfn|Evans|2018|p=119}} Feinler set up a server at the [[Domain name registry|Network Information Center]] (NIC) at Stanford which would work as a directory that could retrieve relevant information about a person or entity.{{Sfn|Evans|2018|p=119}} She and her team worked on the creation of [[Domain name|domains]], with Feinler suggesting that domains be divided by categories based on where the computers were kept.{{Sfn|Evans|2018|p=120}} For example, military computers would have the domain of .mil, computers at educational institutions would have .edu.{{Sfn|Evans|2018|p=120-121}} Feinler worked for NIC until 1989.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wired.com/2012/06/elizabeth-jake-feinler/|title=Before Google and GoDaddy, There Was Elizabeth Feinler|last=Metz|first=Cade|date=June 18, 2012|work=WIRED|access-date=October 14, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> 

Jean E. Sammet served as the first woman president of the [[Association for Computing Machinery]] (ACM), holding the position between 1974 and 1976.{{Sfn|Gürer|1995|p=179}}

[[Adele Goldberg (computer scientist)|Adele Goldberg]] was one of seven programmers that developed [[Smalltalk]] in the 1970s, and wrote the majority of the language's documentation. It was one of the first [[object-oriented programming languages]] the base of the current [[graphic user interface]],<ref name=goldberg>{{cite web|url=https://www.cs.umd.edu/hcil/muiseum/goldberg/goldberg_page.htm|title=Adele Goldberg|publisher=[[University of Maryland, College Park]]|accessdate=October 14, 2018}}</ref> that has its roots in the 1968 [[The Mother of All Demos]] by [[Douglas Engelbart]]. Smalltalk was used by Apple to launch [[Apple Lisa]] in 1983, the first personal computer with a GUI, and a year later its [[Macintosh]]. Windows 1.0, based on the same principles, was launched a few months later in 1985.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2008/12/11/engelbart_celebration/|title=The Mother of All Demos — 150 years ahead of its time|work=The Register|date=December 11, 2008|accessdate=October 19, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnet.com/news/tracing-the-origins-of-the-macintosh/|title=Tracing the Origins of the Macintosh|work=CNet|first=Dan|last=Farber|date=January 21, 2014|accessdate=October 19, 2018}}</ref>

In the late 1970s, women such as Paulson and Sue Finley wrote programs for the [[Voyager program|Voyager mission]].{{Sfn|Holt|2016|p=247}} Voyager continues to carry their codes inside its own memory banks as it leaves the [[Solar System|solar system]].{{Sfn|Holt|2016|p=283-284}} In 1979, [[Ruzena Bajcsy]] founded the General Robotics, Automation, Sensing and Perception (GRASP) Lab at the [[University of Pennsylvania]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.fi.edu/laureates/ruzena-bajcsy|title=Ruzena Bajcsy|date=January 15, 2014|work=The Franklin Institute|access-date=October 24, 2018|language=en}}</ref>

In the mid-70s, [[Joan Margaret Winters]] began working at IBM as part of a "human factors project," called SHARE.<ref name=":72" /> In 1978, Winters was the deputy manager of the project and went on to lead the project between 1983 and 1987.<ref name=":72" /> The SHARE group worked on researching how software should be designed to consider [[Human Factors in Engineering and Design|human factors]].<ref name=":72" />

[[Erna Schneider Hoover]] developed a computerized switching system for telephone calls that would replace switchboards.<ref name=":72" /> Her software patent for the system, issued in 1971, was one of the first software patents ever issued.<ref name=":72" />

=== 1980s ===
[[File:Shelley_Lake_at_Digital_Productions_1983.jpg|alt=Shelley Lake working on computer graphics at Digital Productions, 1983.|thumb|Shelley Lake working on computer graphics at Digital Productions, 1983.]]
[[Gwen Bell]] developed the [[The Computer Museum, Boston|Computer Museum]] in 1980.<ref name=":7">{{Cite web|url=http://history.computer.org/pioneers/bell-g.html|title=Computer Pioneers – Gwen Bell|last=Lee|first=J.A.N.|date=1995|website=Computer Pioneers|publisher=IEEE Computer Society|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=October 18, 2018}}</ref> The museum, which collected computer artifacts became a non-profit organization in 1982 and in 1984, Bell moved it to downtown [[Boston]].<ref name=":7" /> Adele Goldberg served as president of ACM between 1984 and 1986.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.witi.com/center/witimuseum/halloffame/100883/Adele-Goldberg-Founding-Chairman-ParcPlace-Systems,-Inc/|title=Adele Goldberg, Founding Chairman, ParcPlace Systems, Inc|last=|first=|date=|website=WITI – Women in Technology Hall of Fame|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=October 14, 2018}}</ref> In 1986, [[Lixia Zhang]] was the only woman and graduate student to participate in the early Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) meetings.<ref name="interview">{{citation|last=|first=|title=Interview with Lixia Zhang, Professor, Computer Science Department, UCLA, Member of the IAB|date=Spring 2006|url=http://www.internetsociety.org/articles/interview-lixia-zhang-professor-computer-science-department-ucla-member-iab|journal=IETF Journal|volume=|pages=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304023815/http://www.internetsociety.org/articles/interview-lixia-zhang-professor-computer-science-department-ucla-member-iab|archive-date=4 March 2016}}.</ref> Zhang was involved in early Internet development.<ref name="interview" /> 

Sometimes known as the "[[Betsy Ross]] of the personal computer," according to the ''[[The New York Times|New York Times]]'', [[Susan Kare]] worked with [[Steve Jobs]] to design the original icons for the [[Macintosh]].<ref name=":5">{{Cite news|url=https://biztechmagazine.com/article/2012/05/mothers-technology-10-women-who-invented-and-innovated-tech|title=Mothers of Technology: 10 Women Who Invented and Innovated in Tech|last=Riberio|first=Ricky|date=May 11, 2012|work=BizTech|access-date=October 16, 2018|language=en}}</ref><ref name=":6">{{Cite news|url=http://kare.com/articles/nytimes.html|title=The Designer Who Made the Mac Smile|last=Zuckerman|first=Laurence|date=August 26, 1996|work=The New York Times|access-date=October 16, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070221063844/http://kare.com/articles/nytimes.html|archive-date=February 21, 2007}}</ref> Kare designed the moving watch, paintbrush and trash can elements that made using a Mac [[Usability|user-friendly]].<ref name=":5" /><ref name=":6" /> Kare worked for Apple until the mid 1980s, going on to work on icons for [[Windows 3.0]].<ref name=":6" /> Other types of computer graphics were being developed by [[Nadia Magnenat Thalmann]] in Canada. Thalmann started working on computer animation to develop "realistic virtual actors" first at the [[Université de Montréal|University of  Montréal]]  in 1980 and later in 1988 at the [[École Polytechnique Fédérale de Lausanne]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://graphicsinterface.org/awards/chccs-scdhm-achievement/nadia-magnenat-thalmann/|title=Nadia Magnenat Thalmann|last=|first=|date=|work=Graphics Interface|access-date=2018-11-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180727084717/http://graphicsinterface.org/awards/chccs-scdhm-achievement/nadia-magnenat-thalmann/|archive-date=27 July 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>

In the field of [[Human–computer interaction|human computer interaction]] (HCI), French computer scientist, [[Joëlle Coutaz]] developed the [[Presentation–abstraction–control|presentation-abstraction-control]] (PAC) model in 1987.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://hcipioneers.wordpress.com/portfolio/coutaz-joelle/|title=Coutaz, Joëlle|date=2015-12-05|work=Encounters with HCI Pioneers - A Personal Photo Journal|access-date=2018-11-23|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Coutaz|first=Joëlle|date=1987-10-01|title=PAC: AN OBJECT ORIENTED MODEL FOR IMPLEMENTING USER INTERFACES|url=http://dl.acm.org/citation.cfm?id=36111.1045592|journal=ACM SIGCHI Bulletin|volume=19|issue=2|pages=37–41|doi=10.1145/36111.1045592|issn=0736-6906}}</ref> She founded the User Interface group at the Laboratorire de Génie Informatique of IMAG where they worked on different problems relating to user interface and other software tools.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RiV8CwAAQBAJ&lpg=PA43&ots=02PAwG6c8X&dq=Jo%C3%ABlle%20Coutaz%20pac&pg=PA43#v=onepage&q=Jo%C3%ABlle%20Coutaz%20pac&f=false|title=Engineering for HCI|last=Unger|first=Claus|last2=Bass|first2=Leonard J.|date=2016-01-09|publisher=Springer|year=|isbn=9780387349077|location=|pages=43|language=en}}</ref> 

As [[Ethernet]] became the standard for networking computers locally, [[Radia Perlman]], who worked at Digital Equipment Corporation (DEC), was asked to "fix" limitations that Ethernet imposed on large network traffic.{{Sfn|Evans|2018|p=126}} In 1985, Perlman came up with a way to route information packets from one computer to another in an "infinitely scalable" way that allowed large networks like the Internet to function.{{Sfn|Evans|2018|p=126}} Her solution took less than a few days to design and write up.{{Sfn|Evans|2018|p=126}} The name of the algorithm she created is the [[Spanning Tree Protocol]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2014/03/radia-perlman-dont-call-me-the-mother-of-the-internet/284146/|title=Radia Perlman: Don't Call Me the Mother of the Internet|last=Rosen|first=Rebecca J.|date=March 3, 2014|work=The Atlantic|access-date=October 15, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> In 1988, [[Stacy Horn]], who had been introduced to [[Bulletin board system|bulletin board systems]] (BBS) through [[The WELL]], decided to create her own online community in New York, which she called the East Coast Hang Out (ECHO).{{Sfn|Evans|2018|p=134}} Horn invested her own money and pitched the idea for ECHO to others after bankers refused to hear her business plan.{{Sfn|Evans|2018|p=135}} Horn built her BBS using [[Unix|UNIX]], which she and her friends taught to one another.{{Sfn|Evans|2018|p=135-136}} Eventually ECHO moved an office in [[Tribeca]] in the early 1990s and started getting press attention.{{Sfn|Evans|2018|p=136}} ECHO's users could post about topics that interested them, chat with on another and were provided email accounts.{{Sfn|Evans|2018|p=137}} Around half of ECHO's users were women.{{Sfn|Evans|2018|p=139}} ECHO is still online as of 2018.{{Sfn|Evans|2018|p=144}}

Europe was somewhat behind other countries in developing an Internet infrastructure.<ref name=":15">{{Cite news|url=https://siol.net/digisvet/novice/to-je-znanstvenica-ki-je-v-slovenijo-pripeljala-internet-418385|title=To je znanstvenica, ki je v Slovenijo pripeljala internet #intervju|last=Pirnat|first=Andrej J.|date=30 May 2016|work=Siol.net|access-date=2018-11-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170708224026/http://siol.net/digisvet/novice/to-je-znanstvenica-ki-je-v-slovenijo-pripeljala-internet-418385|archive-date=8 July 2017|language=sl}}</ref> A project was developed in the mid-1980s to create an academic network in Europe using the [[Open Systems Interconnection|Open System Interconnection]] (OSI) standards.<ref name=":15" /> [[Borka Jerman Blažič]], a [[Yugoslavia|Yugoslavian]] computer scientist was invited to work on the project.<ref name=":15" /> She was involved in establishing a Yugoslav Research and Academic Network (YUNAC) in 1989 and registered the domain of [[.yu]] for the country.<ref name=":15" />

Computer and video games became popular in the 1980s, but many were primarily action-oriented and not designed from a woman's point of view. Stereotypical characters such as the [[damsel in distress]] featured prominently and consequently were not inviting towards women.<ref name="Suellentrop" /> [[Dona Bailey]] designed ''[[Centipede (video game)|Centipede]]'', where the player shoots insects, as a reaction to such games, later saying "It didn't seem bad to shoot a bug".<ref name="Ortutay2012a">{{cite news |first=Barbara |last=Ortutay |title=Iconic Atari turns 40, tries to stay relevant |url=https://news.yahoo.com/iconic-atari-turns-40-tries-stay-relevant-211822140--finance.html |agency=Associated Press |publisher=Yahoo! News |date=June 29, 2012}}</ref> [[Carol Shaw]], considered to be the first modern female games designer, released a 3D version of [[Tic-tac-toe]] for the [[Atari 2600]] in 1980.<ref name="Suellentrop">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/08/20/arts/video-games/those-underappreciated-female-video-game-pioneers.html|title=Saluting the Women Behind the Screen|first=Chris|last=Suellentrop|newspaper=New York Times|date=October 20, 2014|accessdate=October 13, 2018}}</ref> [[Roberta Williams]] and her husband Ken, founded [[Sierra Online]] and pioneered the [[graphic adventure game]] format in ''[[Mystery House]]'' and the ''[[King's Quest]]'' series. The games had a friendly [[graphical user interface]] and introduced humor and puzzles. Cited as an important game designer, her influenced spread from Sierra to other companies such as [[LucasArts]] and beyond.<ref>{{cite book|title=Vintage Games: An Insider Look at the History of Grand Theft Auto, Super Mario, and the Most Influential Games of All Time|first=Bill|last=Loguidice|first2=Matt|last2=Barton|publisher=Taylor & Francis|p=215|year=2012|isbn=978-1-136-13757-0}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/1980s-roberta-williams-brought-graphic-adventure-games-home-180962160/|title=The Pioneer of Graphic Adventure Games Was a Woman|first=Kat|last=Eschner|magazine=Smithsonian Magazine|date=February 16, 2017|accessdate=October 13, 2018}}</ref> [[Brenda Laurel]] worked on porting games from [[Arcade game|arcade]] versions to the [[Atari 8-bit family|Atari 400]] and [[Atari 8-bit family|Atari 800]] computers in the late 1970s and early 1980s.{{Sfn|Evans|2018|p=226}} She then went to work for [[Activision]], writing the manual for ''[[Maniac Mansion]]''.{{Sfn|Evans|2018|p=226}} 

1984 was the year of Women Into Science and Engineering (WISE). A 1984 report by [[Ebury Publishing]] reported that in a typical family, only 5% of mothers and 19% of daughters were using a computer at home, compared to 25% of fathers and 51% of sons. To counteract this, the company launched a series of software titles designed towards women and publicised in ''[[Good Housekeeping]]''.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Computer machismo|magazine=Sinclair User|date=November 1984|p=12|url=http://live.worldofspectrum.org/infoseek/magazines/sinclair-user/32#12}}</ref> Anita Borg, who had been noticing that women were under-represented in computer science, founded an email support group, [[Systers]], in 1987.<ref name=":8">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/24671349/|title=Anita Borg; Helped Women Break Industry's 'Silicone Ceiling'|last=|first=|date=April 10, 2003|work=The Boston Globe|access-date=October 19, 2018|language=en|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>

===1990s===
[[File:Jaimelevyrussell.jpg|thumb|left|upright|[[Jaime Levy]] helped popularise the e-Zine in the 1990s.]]
By the 1990s, computing was dominated by men. The proportion of female computer science graduates peaked in 1984 around 37 per cent, and then steadily declined. Although the end of the 20th century saw an increase in women scientists and engineers, this did not hold true for computing, which stagnated.{{sfn|Abbate|2012|p=145}} Despite this, they were very involved in working on hypertext and hypermedia projects in the late 1980s and early 1990s.{{Sfn|Evans|2018|p=161}} A team of women at [[Brown University]], including Nicole Yankelovich and [[Karen Catlin]], developed [[Intermedia (hypertext)|Intermedia]] and invented the anchor link.{{Sfn|Evans|2018|p=161-162}} [[Apple Inc.|Apple]] partially funded their project and incorporated their concepts into Apple [[Operating system|operating systems]].{{Sfn|Evans|2018|p=162}} [[Sun Microsystems]] Sun Link Service was developed by Amy Pearl.{{Sfn|Evans|2018|p=162}} [[Janet Walker]] developed the first system to use bookmarks when she created the [[Symbolics Document Examiner]].{{Sfn|Evans|2018|p=162}} In 1989, [[Wendy Hall]] created a [[hypertext]] project called [[Microcosm (hypermedia system)|Microcosm]], which was based on digitized [[multimedia]] material found in the Mountbatten archive.{{Sfn|Evans|2018|p=159}} [[Cathy Marshall (hypertext developer)|Cathy Marshall]] worked on the [[NoteCards]] system at [[PARC (company)|Xerox PARC]].{{Sfn|Evans|2018|p=164}} NoteCards went on to influence Apple's [[HyperCard]].{{Sfn|Evans|2018|p=164-165}} As the Internet became the [[World Wide Web]], developers like Hall adapted their programs to include Web viewers.{{Sfn|Evans|2018|p=169}} Her Microcosm was especially adaptable to new technologies, including animation and 3-D models.{{Sfn|Evans|2018|p=171}} In 1994, Hall helped organize the first conference for the Web.{{Sfn|Evans|2018|p=174}} 

[[Sarah Allen (software developer)|Sarah Allen]], the co-founder of [[Adobe After Effects|After Effects]], co-founded a commercial software company called CoSA in 1990.<ref name=":3">{{Cite news|url=https://www.ncwit.org/profile/sarah-allen|title=Sarah Allen|work=National Center for Women & Information Technology|access-date=October 15, 2018|language=en}}</ref> In 1995, she started working on the [[Shockwave (game portal)|Shockwave]] team for [[Macromedia]] where she was the lead developer of the Shockwave Mulituser Server, the [[Adobe Flash Media Server|Flash Media Server]] and [[Flash Video|Flash video]].<ref name=":3" />

Following the increased popularity of the Internet in the 1990s, online spaces were set up to cater for women, including the online community [[Women's WIRE]]<ref name="auto">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/24408141/|title=Wired Women of the Internet|last=|first=|date=October 16, 1996|work=The Paducah Sun|access-date=October 11, 2018|language=en|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> and the technical and support forum [[LinuxChix]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.zdnet.com/2100-9595_22-515695.html?legacy=zdnn|title=She-geeks confess love for Linux|author=Lisa Bowman|date=September 15, 1999|work=[[ZDNet]] News|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070625151809/http://news.zdnet.com/2100-9595_22-515695.html?legacy=zdnn|archivedate=June 25, 2007|deadurl=yes}}</ref> Women's WIRE, launched by Nancy Rhine and Ellen Pack in October 1993, was the first Internet company to specifically target this demographic.<ref name="auto"/>{{Sfn|Evans|2018|p=206}} A conference for women in computer-related jobs, the [[Grace Hopper Celebration of Women in Computing]], was first launched in 1994 by Anita Borg.<ref name=":8" />

Game designer Brenda Laurel started working at [[Interval Research Corporation|Interval Research]] in 1992, and began to think about the differences in the way girls and boys experienced playing video games.{{Sfn|Evans|2018|p=227-228}} After interviewing around 1,000 children and 500 adults, she determined that games weren't designed with girls' interests in mind.{{Sfn|Evans|2018|p=228}} The girls she spoke with wanted more games with open worlds and characters they could interact with.{{Sfn|Evans|2018|p=229}} Her research led to Interval Research giving Laurel's research team their own company in 1996, [[Purple Moon]].{{Sfn|Evans|2018|p=229}} Also in 1996, [[Mattel|Mattel's]] game, ''[[Barbie Fashion Designer]]'', became the first best-selling game for girls.{{Sfn|Evans|2018|p=230}} Purple Moon's first two games based on a character called Rockett, made it to the 100 best-selling games in the years they were released.{{Sfn|Evans|2018|p=233}} In 1999, Mattel bought out Purple Moon.{{Sfn|Evans|2018|p=235}}

[[Jaime Levy]] created the one of the first e-Zines in the early 1990s, starting with ''CyberRag'', which included articles, games and animations loaded onto diskettes that anyone with a [[MacOS|Mac]] could access.<ref name=":2">{{Cite news|url=http://nymag.com/intelligencer/2018/04/claire-evanss-broad-band-excerpt.html|title=The Untold Story of Jaime Levy, Punk-Rock Cyber-Publishing Pioneer|last=Evans|first=Claire L.|work=Intelligencer|access-date=October 15, 2018|language=en}}</ref> Later, she renamed the [[zine]] to ''Electronic Hollywood.''<ref name=":2" /> [[Billy Idol]] commissioned Levy to create a disk for his album, ''[[Cyberpunk (album)|Cyberpunk]]''.<ref name=":2" /> She was hired to be the creative director of the online magazine, ''[[Word Magazine|Word]]'', in 1995.<ref name=":2" />

Cyberfeminists, [[VNS Matrix]], made up of [[Josephine Starrs]], [[Julianne Pierce|Juliane Pierce]], Francesca da Rimini and [[Virginia Barratt]], created art in the early 1990s linking computer technology and women's bodies.{{Sfn|Evans|2018|p=238}} In 1997, there was a gathering of [[Cyberfeminism|cyberfeminists]] in [[Kassel]], called the First Cyberfeminist International.{{Sfn|Evans|2018|p=240}}

In China, [[Hu Qiheng]], was the leader of the team who installed the first [[Internet protocol suite|TCP/IP]] connection for China, connecting to the Internet on April 20, 1994.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=d4M_DwAAQBAJ&lpg=PP123|title=The SAGE Handbook of Social Media|date=2017|publisher=SAGE|isbn=1473995795|editor1-last=Burgess|editor1-first=Jean|pages=123–24|accessdate=25 March 2018|editor2-last=Marwick|editor2-first=Alice|editor3-last=Poell|editor3-first=Thomas}}</ref> In 1995, [[Rosemary Candlin]] went to write software for [[CERN]] in [[Geneva]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ethw.org/Oral-History:Rosemary_Candlin|title=Oral-History:Rosemary Candlin|last=Abbate|first=Janet|date=19 September 2001|website=Engineering and Technology History Wiki|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-11-22}}</ref> In the early 1990s, [[Nancy Hafkin]] was an important figure in working with the [[Association for Progressive Communications]] (APC) in enabling email connections in 10 African countries.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.internethalloffame.org/inductees/nancy-hafkin|title=Nancy Hafkin|last=|first=|date=|website=Internet Hall of Fame|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181121204604/https://www.internethalloffame.org/inductees/nancy-hafkin|archive-date=21 November 2018|dead-url=|access-date=2018-11-29}}</ref> Starting in 1999, [[Anne-Marie Eklund Löwinder]] began to work with [[Domain Name System Security Extensions]] (DNSSEC) in [[Sweden]].<ref name=":16">{{Cite web|url=https://www.internethalloffame.org/inductees/anne-marie-eklund-l%C3%B6winder|title=Anne-Marie Eklund Löwinder|last=|first=|date=|website=Internet Hall of Fame|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180914184501/https://www.internethalloffame.org/inductees/anne-marie-eklund-l%C3%B6winder|archive-date=14 September 2018|dead-url=|access-date=2018-11-29}}</ref> She later made sure that the domain, [[.se]], was the world's first top level domain name to be signed with DNSSEC.<ref name=":16" />

===2000s===
[[File:Marissa Mayer LeWeb 2008 VI.jpg|alt=Marissa Mayer|thumb|upright|Former vice-president of [[Google]] Search Products and User Experience, former president and CEO of [[Yahoo!]], [[Marissa Mayer]].]]
In the 21st century, several attempts have been made to reduce the gender disparity in IT and get more women involved in computing again. A 2001 survey found that while both sexes use computers and the internet in equal measure, women were still five times less likely to choose it as a career or study the subject beyond standard secondary education.{{sfn|Frieze|Quesenberry|2015|p=15}} Journalist [[Emily Chang (journalist)|Emily Chang]] said a key problem has been [[personality test]]s in job interviews and the belief that good programmers are introverts, which tends to self-select the stereotype of an antisocial white male nerd.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/mar/17/sexual-harassment-silicon-valley-emily-chang-brotopia-interview|title=Why sexism is rife in Silicon Valley|first=Emily|last=Chang|newspaper=The Guardian|date=March 17, 2018|accessdate=October 13, 2018}}</ref>

In 2004, the [[National Center for Women & Information Technology]] was established by [[Lucy Sanders]] to address the gender gap.<ref>{{cite web|last=Ericson|first=Cathie|title=Intrepid Woman: Lucinda (Lucy) Sanders: CEO and Co-founder of the National Center for Women & Information Technology (NCWIT) |url=http://www.theglasshammer.com/news/2014/10/17/intrepid-woman-lucy-sanders-ceo-and-co-founder-of-the-national-center-for-women-information-technology-ncwit/|work=The Glass Hammer|publisher=Evolved People Media LLC|accessdate=November 12, 2014|date=October 17, 2014}}</ref> [[Carnegie Mellon University]] has made a concerted attempt to increase gender diversity in the computer science field, by selecting students based on a wide criteria including leadership ability, a sense of "giving back to the community" and high attainment in maths and science, instead of traditional computer programming expertise. As well as increase the intake of women into CMU, the programme resulted in better quality students overall, as they found the increased diversity made for a stronger team.{{sfn|Frieze|Quesenberry|2015|p=25-27}}

=== 2010s ===
Despite the pioneering work of some designers, video games are still considered biased towards men. A 2013 survey by the [[International Game Developers Association]] revealed only 22% of game designers are women, although this is substantially higher than figures in previous decades.<ref name="Suellentrop" /> Working to bring inclusion to the world of open source project development, [[Coraline Ada Ehmke]] drafts the [[Contributor Covenant]] in 2014.<ref name=":9">{{Cite news|url=https://www.wired.com/story/woman-bringing-civility-to-open-source-projects/|title=The Woman Bringing Civility to Open Source Projects|last=Finley|first=Klint|date=September 26, 2018|work=WIRED|access-date=October 23, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> By 2018, over 40,000 software projects have started using the Contributor Covenant, including [[TensorFlow]], [[Vue.js|Vue]] and [[Linux]].<ref name=":9" />

In 2017, [[Michelle Simmons]] founded the first [[quantum computing]] company in [[Australia]].<ref name=":4">{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/science/meet-the-woman-leading-race-to-build-worlds-first-quantum-computer/articleshow/64126927.cms|title=Meet the woman leading race to build world's first quantum computer|date=May 11, 2018|work=The Economic Times|access-date=October 15, 2018}}</ref> The team, which has made "great strides" in 2018, plans to develop a 10-[[qubit]] prototype silicon quantum integrated circuit by 2022.<ref name=":4" /> Also in 2017, [[Doina Precup]] became the head of [[DeepMind]] Montreal, working on [[artificial intelligence]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deepmind.com/blog/strengthening-our-commitment-canadian-research/|title=Strengthening our commitment to Canadian research|last=|first=|date=|website=DeepMind|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181009181350/https://deepmind.com/blog/strengthening-our-commitment-canadian-research/|archive-date=9 October 2018|dead-url=|access-date=2018-11-23}}</ref>

== Gender gap in computing ==
{{Main|Gender disparity in computing}}
One of the biggest problems facing women in computing in the modern era is that they often find themselves working in an environment that is largely unpleasant, so they don't stay on in the careers in programming and technology.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://time.com/4892094/google-diversity-history-memo/|title=Women in Tech and the History Behind That Controversial Google Diversity Memo|last=Waxman|first=Olivia B.|date=August 8, 2017|website=Time|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=October 18, 2018}}</ref> In 2013, a [[National Public Radio]] report said 20% of computer programmers in the US are female.<ref>{{Cite episode|publisher = National Public Radio| credits = Laura Sydell (Director)|title = Blazing The Trail For Female Programmers|series = All Tech Considered|accessdate = June 7, 2013|date=April 29, 2013|url=https://www.npr.org/blogs/alltechconsidered/2013/04/29/178810467/blazing-the-trail-for-female-programmers}}</ref>{{sfn|Margolis|Fisher|2003|p=8}} There is no general consensus for any key reason there are less women in computing. In 2017, James Damore was fired from [[Google]] after claiming there was a biological reason for a lack of female computer scientists.<ref name=devlin_hern>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2017/aug/08/why-are-there-so-few-women-in-tech-the-truth-behind-the-google-memo|title=Why are there so few women in tech? The truth behind the Google memo|first=Hannah|last=Devlin|first2=Alex|last2=Hern|newspaper=The Guardian|date=August 8, 2017|accessdate=October 18, 2017}}</ref> The following year, [[Wikipedia]] was criticised for not having an article about scientist [[Donna Strickland]] until shortly after she won the Nobel Prize for Physics, which was attributed to a severe gender disparity of the site's editors.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/nobel-prize-winner-physics-2018-donna-strickland-wikipedia-entry-deleted-sexism-equality-a8572006.html|title=Donna Strickland's treatment on Wikipedia shows how women have long been excluded from science|newspaper=The Independent|date=October 6, 2018|accessdate=October 19, 2018}}</ref>

In 1991, [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] undergraduate [[Ellen Spertus]] wrote an essay "Why Are There So Few Women in Computer Science?", which complained about inherent sexism in IT, which was responsible for a lack of women in computing.{{sfn|Abbate|2012|p=150}} She subsequently taught computer science at [[Mills College]], [[Oakland, California|Oakland]] in order to increase interest in IT for women.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2003/08/21/technology/3-women-3-paths-10-years-on.html|title=3 Women, 3 Paths, 10 Years On|first=Katie|last=Hafner|newspaper=New York Times|date=August 21, 2003|accessdate=October 13, 2018}}</ref> A key problem is a lack of female role models in the IT industry, alongside computer programmers in fiction and the media generally being male.<ref name=stanfordcs>{{cite news|last1=McBride|first1=Sarah|title=Computer science now top major for women at Stanford University|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-women-technology-stanford-idUSKCN0S32F020151009|newspaper=Reuters|accessdate=January 5, 2016|date=2015-10-09}}</ref> The [[University of Southampton]]'s [[Wendy Hall]] has said the attractiveness of computers to women decreased significantly in the 1980s when they "were sold as toys for boys", and believes the cultural stigma has remained ever since, and may even be getting worse.<ref name=devlin_hern/> Kathleen Lehman, project manager of the BRAID Initiative at [[UCLA]] has said a problem is that typically women aim for perfection and feel disillusioned when code does not [[compiler|compile]], whereas men may simply treat it as a learning experience.<ref name=sax/> A report in the ''[[Daily Telegraph]]'' suggested that women generally prefer people-facing jobs, which many computing and IT positions do not have, while men prefer jobs geared towards objects and tasks.<ref name="JRigby">{{cite news|last1=Rigby|first1=Jennifer|title=Is there any science behind the lack of women in science?|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/women/womens-health/11401344/STEM-Is-there-any-science-behind-the-lack-of-women-in-science.html|website=The Telegraph|publisher=The Telegraph|accessdate=October 26, 2016|date=2015-02-16}}</ref><ref name="jobprefs">{{cite journal|last1=Radford|first1=John|last2=Holdstock|first2=Leonard|title=Gender Differences in Higher Education Aims between Computing and Psychology Students|journal=Research in Science & Technological Education|doi=10.1080/0263514950130206|volume=13|issue=2|pages=163–176|year=1995}}</ref>

The gender disparity in IT is not global. The ratio of female to male computer scientists is significantly higher in India compared to the West.<ref name=devlin_hern/> In Europe, Bulgaria and Romania have the highest rates of women going into computer programming.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.zdnet.com/article/women-in-tech-why-bulgaria-and-romania-are-leading-in-software-engineering/|title=Women in tech: Why Bulgaria and Romania are leading in software engineering {{!}} ZDNet|last=Fiscutean|first=Andrada|date=June 13, 2017|work=ZDNet|access-date=October 23, 2018|language=en}}</ref> In government universities in Saudi Arabia in 2014, Arab women made up 59% of students enrolled in computer science.{{Sfn|Islam|2017|p=13}} However, the ratio of African American female computer scientists in the US is significantly lower than the national average.<ref name=sax>{{cite news|url=http://newsroom.ucla.edu/stories/cracking-the-code:-why-aren-t-more-women-majoring-in-computer-science|title=Cracking the code: Why aren't more women majoring in computer science?|first=Linda|last=Sax|work=UCLA Newsroom|date=June 26, 2017|accessdate=October 18, 2018}}</ref> It has been suggested there is a greater gap in countries where people of both sexes are treated more equally, contradicting any theories that society in general is to blame for any disparity.<ref name="RLippa">{{cite journal|last1=Lippa|first1=Richard|title=Gender Differences in Personality and Interests: When, Where, and Why?|doi=10.1111/j.1751-9004.2010.00320.x|volume=4|issue=11|journal=Social and Personality Psychology Compass|pages=1098–1110|year=2010}}</ref>

== Turing Award recipients ==
[[File:Shafi Goldwasser.JPG|alt=Shafi Goldwasser|thumb|[[Shafi Goldwasser]] was the 2012 [[Turing Award|Turing award]] recipient for her collaborative work in [[cryptography]].]]
The [[Association for Computing Machinery]] [[Turing Award]], sometimes referred to as the "Nobel Prize" of computing, was named in honor of Alan Turing. It award has been won by three women between 1966 and 2015.<ref name="acmturing">{{cite web|title=Official ACM Turing award website|url=http://amturing.acm.org/award_winners/liskov_1108679.cfm|website=amturing.acm.org|publisher=ACM|accessdate=February 14, 2015}}</ref>
* 2006 – [[Frances E. Allen|Francis "Fran" Elizabeth Allen]]
* 2008 – [[Barbara Liskov]]
* 2012 – [[Shafi Goldwasser]]

== Karen Spärk Jones Award recipients ==
The [[British Computer Society]] Information Retrieval Specialist Group (BCS IRSG) in conjunction with the British Computer Society created an award in 2008 to commemorate the achievements of [[Karen Spärck Jones]], a Professor Emerita of Computers and Information at the [[University of Cambridge]] and one of the most remarkable women in computer science. The KSJ award has been won by four women between 2009 and 2017:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://irsg.bcs.org/ksjaward.php|title=KSJ Award|website=irsg.bcs.org|access-date=October 8, 2018}}</ref>

*2009 – [[Mirella Lapata]]
* 2012 – [[Diane Kelly (computer scientist)|Diane Kelly]]
* 2015 – [[Emine Yilmaz]]
*2016 – [[Jaime Teevan]]

== Organizations ==
<!-- PLEASE NOTE: This list is restricted to organisations which have a Wikipedia page. Any others will be removed. -->

Several important groups have been established to encourage women in the IT industry. The [[Association for Women in Computing]] was one of the first and is dedicated to promoting the advancement of women in computing professions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.awc-hq.org/home.html|title=Association for Women in Computing |publisher=|accessdate=August 10, 2015}}</ref> The [[CRA-W: Committee on the Status of Women in Computing Research]] established in 1991 focused on increasing the number of women in Computer Science and Engineering (CSE) research and education at all levels.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cra.org/cra-w/history/|title=The History of CRA-W|publisher=CRA Women|accessdate=October 15, 2018}}</ref> [[AnitaB.org]] runs the [[Grace Hopper Celebration of Women in Computing]] yearly conference. The [[National Center for Women & Information Technology]] is a nonprofit that aims to  increase the number of women in technology and computing.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ncwit.org/about|title=About Us|publisher=}}</ref> The [[Women in Technology International]] (WITI) is a global organization dedicated to the advancement of women in business and technology.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://singularityhub.com/2018/07/29/how-technology-is-helping-close-the-gender-gap-and-empower-women/|title=How Technology Is Helping Close the Gender Gap and Empower Women|last=Bidshahri|first=Raya|date=July 29, 2018|work=Singularity Hub|access-date=October 15, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>

Some major societies and groups have offshoots dedicated to women. The [[ACM-W| Association for Computing Machinery's Council on Women in Computing]] (ACM-W) has over 36,000 members.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://women.acm.org/ACMW-Webpage/Information/Files/ACM-W_Brochure.pdf|title=ACM-W Brochure|publisher=}}</ref> [[BCSWomen]] is a women-only specialist group of the [[British Computer Society]], founded in 2001.<ref>{{cite journal|first=Justin|last=Richards|url=http://www.computerweekly.com/Articles/2006/04/04/215212/bcswomen-celebrates-five-years.htm|title=BCSWomen celebrates five years|journal=[[Computer Weekly]]|date=April 4, 2006|accessdate=October 15, 2018}}.</ref> In Ireland, the charity [[Teen Turn]] run after school training and work placements for girls<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.siliconrepublic.com/careers/teen-turn-goboforce-xtremepush-women-tech|title=Teen-Turn: How companies are bringing more women into STEM|last=Darmody|first=Jenny|date=July 13, 2017|work=Silicon Republic|access-date=November 15, 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref>, and [[Women in Technology and Science]] (WITS) advocate for the inclusion and promotion of women within STEM industries.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.siliconrepublic.com/innovation/mary-mulvihill-science-communication|title=The stories that she told: Mary Mulvihill (1959–2015)|last=Sheridan|first=Cormac|date=February 13, 2018|work=Silicon Republic|access-date=November 15, 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref>

The [[Women's Technology Empowerment Centre]] (W.TEC) is a non-profit organisation focused on providing technology education and mentoring to Nigerian women and girls.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.w-teconline.org|title=The Women's Technology Empowerment Centre – W.TEC|publisher=|accessdate=October 26, 2014}}</ref> [[Black Girls Code]] is a non-profit focused on providing technology education to young African-American women.<ref name="Robehmed">{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/natalierobehmed/2013/08/30/black-girls-code-tackles-tech-inclusion/|title=Black Girls Code Tackles Tech Inclusion|last=Robehmed|first=Natalie|date=August 30, 2013|work=[[Forbes]]|accessdate=April 16, 2014}}</ref>

Other organisations dedicated to women in IT include [[Girl develop it|Girl Develop It]], a nonprofit organization that provides affordable programs for adult women interested in learning web and software development in a judgment-free environment,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.girldevelopit.com/about|title=About  –  Girl Develop It|website=www.girldevelopit.com}}</ref> [[Girl Geek Dinners]], an International group for women of all ages, [[Girls Who Code]]: a national non-profit organization dedicated to closing the gender gap in technology,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://girlswhocode.com/about-us/|title=About Us – Girls Who Code|publisher=}}</ref> [[LinuxChix]], a women-oriented community in the [[Open-source software|open source]] movement<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.zdnet.com/2100-9595_22-515695.html?legacy=zdnn|title=She-geeks confess love for Linux|work=[[ZDNet]] News|author=Lisa Bowman|date=September 15, 1999|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070625151809/http://news.zdnet.com/2100-9595_22-515695.html?legacy=zdnn|archivedate=June 25, 2007|deadurl=yes}}</ref> and [[Systers]], a moderated listserv dedicated to mentoring women in the IT industry.<ref name=AAS>{{cite news|last=Kadaba|first=Linda|title='Systers' carve out Internet niche|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=AASB&p_theme=aasb&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EAD979F537A7050&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|accessdate=September 21, 2012|newspaper=[[Austin American-Statesman]]|date=June 26, 1995}}</ref>

